               <msContents class="#STM">
                  <summary><p>The <title xml:lang="ta">Kūrmapurāṇam</title> is a Tamil version of the Sanskrit <title xml:lang="sa">Kūrmapurāṇam</title> by the <placeName xml:lang="ta">Teṉkāci</placeName> ("Southern <placeName xml:lang="sa">Kāśī</placeName>") king <persName xml:lang="ta">Ativīrarāmapāṇṭiyaṉ</persName>, who ruled in the second half of the 16th century. See Raghavan (1960, p. 228‒229). On <persName xml:lang="ta">Ativīrarāmapāṇṭiyaṉ</persName>, best known for his <title xml:lang="ta">Naiṭatam</title>, a Tamil version of the Sanskrit <title xml:lang="sa">Naiṣadha</title> by <persName xml:lang="sa">Harṣa</persName>, see Shulman (2012, pp. 155ff.).</p>

<p>As the manuscript is fragile, it has not been possible to examine it exhaustively.</p>
<p>The text, in 94 chapters and 3723 stanzas, appears to be complete.</p>
<p>Description based on the examination of the original manuscript (July 2020).</p>
<p>Dimensions assessed at the time of examination.</p> 
                  </summary>
                  
